WEBVTT

00:01.418 --> 00:05.422
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:05.422 --> 00:07.424
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:07.424 --> 00:13.305
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.057 --> 00:16.725
<i>- I'm Rob Singleton.</i>

00:16.725 --> 00:18.727
I was a firefighter
for 25 years.

00:18.727 --> 00:21.939
I had to retire because they
found out I had leukemia.

00:21.939 --> 00:24.608
<i>Lost probably 100 pounds</i>

00:24.608 --> 00:26.526
<i>and was very weak.</i>

00:26.526 --> 00:27.611
I started back with
my knife making

00:27.611 --> 00:29.279
because I loved it so much.

00:29.279 --> 00:31.323
<i>It really helped me get</i>
<i>my strength back</i>

00:31.323 --> 00:33.242
<i>and do what I enjoy.</i>

00:33.242 --> 00:34.868
<i>- My name is Jason Fry</i>
<i>from Lubbock, Texas.</i>

00:34.868 --> 00:36.411
I started making knives

00:36.411 --> 00:38.330
because I was skinning
too many raccoons

00:38.330 --> 00:39.706
<i>and I needed more sharp stuff,</i>
<i>and so I thought,</i>

00:39.706 --> 00:41.500
<i>"Well, heck,</i>
<i>I'll just make one."</i>

00:41.500 --> 00:44.294
I've run trap lines.
I've done competitive fishing.

00:44.294 --> 00:45.963
<i>Don't want to say</i>
<i>I've picked up road kill,</i>

00:45.963 --> 00:47.756
but a five-dollar bill is
a five-dollar bill, man.

00:47.756 --> 00:49.883
[laughs]

00:49.883 --> 00:52.344
<i>- I'm Michael Kerley.</i>
<i>I'm from Illinois.</i>

00:52.344 --> 00:53.929
I am very competitive.

00:53.929 --> 00:55.305
I have a friend at home
that me and him

00:55.305 --> 00:57.266
<i>go head-to-head all the time</i>

00:57.266 --> 00:59.309
on the spiciest food
we can find.

00:59.309 --> 01:01.270
<i>I've won almost every time.</i>

01:01.270 --> 01:03.855
My friends at home call me
Spicy Mike.

01:03.855 --> 01:06.692
<i>- My name is Ryan Brewer.</i>
<i>I am 20 years old.</i>

01:06.692 --> 01:08.026
If you look at
the competitors, we got--

01:08.026 --> 01:10.571
anvil one, beard,
anvil two, beard,

01:10.571 --> 01:12.656
<i>anvil three, really big beard.</i>

01:12.656 --> 01:13.991
<i>And there's me at anvil four.</i>

01:13.991 --> 01:15.409
Sometimes I wish
I had a beard,

01:15.409 --> 01:17.202
but I think in this competition

01:17.202 --> 01:18.912
it's just more likely
that it would catch on fire.

01:18.912 --> 01:20.706
So I think I'm good where I am.

01:20.706 --> 01:23.917
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:23.917 --> 01:26.712
Each of you is here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:26.712 --> 01:28.714
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:28.714 --> 01:30.757
specifically designed
to push you to your limits,

01:30.757 --> 01:33.093
all in front of
a panel of expert judges.

01:33.093 --> 01:34.678
These are the men who decide
which of you

01:34.678 --> 01:36.179
will be our next
"Forged In Fire" champion

01:36.179 --> 01:38.640
and take home
that check for $10,000.

01:38.640 --> 01:40.642
Let's go ahead
and meet your judges now.

01:40.642 --> 01:43.854
Up first, ABS mastersmith
J. Neilson,

01:43.854 --> 01:46.940
historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

01:46.940 --> 01:49.609
edged-weapons specialist
Doug Marcaida.

01:49.609 --> 01:51.028
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:51.028 --> 01:52.571
All right, gentlemen.

01:52.571 --> 01:54.323
Let's just barrel
right into this.

01:54.323 --> 01:55.824
In your first round
of competition today,

01:55.824 --> 01:57.659
you'll be using this.

01:57.659 --> 01:59.453
- Man, it's small.

01:59.453 --> 02:00.704
I'm wondering what he's got
hidden under there.

02:00.704 --> 02:02.456
<i>I'm thinking ball bearings.</i>

02:02.456 --> 02:04.291
<i>I'm thinking little stubs</i>
<i>of something.</i>

02:04.291 --> 02:10.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:10.047 --> 02:11.923
[chuckles]

02:11.923 --> 02:14.384
<i>How do I make a knife out</i>
<i>of nothing?</i>

02:14.384 --> 02:17.596
- This is a staple here
in our forge--

02:17.596 --> 02:19.348
the whiskey barrel.

02:19.348 --> 02:21.099
In the first round
of competition,

02:21.099 --> 02:22.434
we're going from barrels
to blades.

02:22.434 --> 02:23.894
- [chuckles]

02:23.894 --> 02:25.646
- You'll be harvesting
the steel

02:25.646 --> 02:27.856
that you need from this barrel

02:27.856 --> 02:29.691
in order
to forge signature blades.

02:29.691 --> 02:31.318
- All that stuff's curved.

02:31.318 --> 02:32.444
<i>How am I gonna make</i>
<i>a straight knife</i>

02:32.444 --> 02:34.029
<i>out of all this curved metal?</i>

02:34.029 --> 02:35.656
- Keep in mind that
in the second round,

02:35.656 --> 02:37.491
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:37.491 --> 02:39.368
to turn them
into fully functional weapons

02:39.368 --> 02:42.079
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:42.079 --> 02:44.456
in a whiskey barrel ring chop

02:44.456 --> 02:47.959
and for edge retention in a
good old-fashioned apple slice.

02:47.959 --> 02:50.295
You will have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

02:50.295 --> 02:52.255
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:52.255 --> 02:54.341
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:54.341 --> 02:57.010
Your ten-minute
design window starts...

02:57.010 --> 02:59.179
now.

02:59.179 --> 03:01.682
Let's talk a little bit
about the steel on this barrel.

03:01.682 --> 03:04.101
Obviously the bands
are what these guys

03:04.101 --> 03:05.519
are gonna be going for.

03:05.519 --> 03:07.354
It's pretty thin stuff.

03:07.354 --> 03:09.106
- Well, that's part of
the trick to this.

03:09.106 --> 03:11.024
It's a thinner stock.

03:11.024 --> 03:13.568
They could stack it up
and forge into a solid chunk.

03:13.568 --> 03:15.946
- I'm shooting for a more
recurve fighter-style knife,

03:15.946 --> 03:17.656
<i>because I think</i>
<i>it'll stand up pretty well</i>

03:17.656 --> 03:19.449
<i>against the barrel chop.</i>

03:19.449 --> 03:21.243
<i>It has a lot of forward</i>
<i>balance to it,</i>

03:21.243 --> 03:23.370
<i>but it's not</i>
<i>an overly heavy blade.</i>

03:23.370 --> 03:27.040
- [sighs, humming]

03:27.040 --> 03:28.792
The blade I'm designing
I would classify it

03:28.792 --> 03:30.710
more as a camp knife.

03:30.710 --> 03:32.671
<i>I'm choosing this type</i>
<i>of blade</i>

03:32.671 --> 03:34.756
<i>because it's a blade</i>
<i>I'm comfortable with making.</i>

03:34.756 --> 03:38.093
And I'm hoping that I have
enough steel to finish it.

03:38.093 --> 03:40.220
<i>- I'm planning</i>
<i>to forge a hybrid</i>

03:40.220 --> 03:42.013
between a competition chopper
and a slicer.

03:42.013 --> 03:44.683
<i>The design is</i>
<i>a little more focused</i>

03:44.683 --> 03:47.144
<i>toward the chop side</i>
<i>of things.</i>

03:47.144 --> 03:48.645
<i>I'm a pretty competitive guy.</i>

03:48.645 --> 03:50.397
<i>Not so much in bladesmithing,</i>

03:50.397 --> 03:52.149
<i>but I do competitive</i>
<i>ballroom dancing.</i>

03:52.149 --> 03:55.068
So you might see some
fancy footwork on the floor.

03:55.068 --> 03:56.736
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:56.736 --> 03:58.447
- I'm gonna make
a Texas bowie.

03:58.447 --> 04:00.532
<i>It'll be long and thin</i>
<i>and tapered</i>

04:00.532 --> 04:02.451
<i>with a good</i>
<i>straight clip point.</i>

04:02.451 --> 04:04.369
<i>I want to build a bowie</i>
<i>that nobody'll mess with,</i>

04:04.369 --> 04:06.079
'cause you don't mess
with Texas.

04:06.079 --> 04:08.540
- Bladesmiths,
your design period is closed.

04:08.540 --> 04:11.168
Your three-hour forge time
starts...

04:11.168 --> 04:13.170
now.

04:13.170 --> 04:14.963
- Off we go.

04:14.963 --> 04:16.423
- So you want to grind
or hold it?

04:16.423 --> 04:18.133
- I'll grind.
- Got it.

04:18.133 --> 04:20.343
- So what's the basic strategy?

04:20.343 --> 04:24.055
Cut 'em. Clean 'em. Stack 'em.
Tack 'em. Heat 'em. Whack 'em.

04:24.055 --> 04:25.932
- That's pretty much it.

04:25.932 --> 04:27.768
There's only so much
of that thin band steel

04:27.768 --> 04:29.311
on there that's good.
- Yeah.

04:29.311 --> 04:30.645
- So they might not
have enough steel.

04:30.645 --> 04:32.189
- They're gonna have
to supplement

04:32.189 --> 04:34.024
that hardenable steel
with something.

04:34.024 --> 04:35.817
- That's what I'm thinking.

04:35.817 --> 04:39.780
- Coming up short on steel
is never an excuse,

04:39.780 --> 04:41.907
especially when you've got
a whole barrel

04:41.907 --> 04:45.452
full of mild steel in the
back-left corner of this forge,

04:45.452 --> 04:47.871
and you can have as much
of it as you want.

04:47.871 --> 04:49.539
<i>- I'm gonna take</i>

04:49.539 --> 04:51.124
<i>the high-carbon steel</i>
<i>from the barrel,</i>

04:51.124 --> 04:53.335
and I'm gonna laminate
that together.

04:53.335 --> 04:55.045
<i>I'm not going for</i>
<i>the mild steel.</i>

04:55.045 --> 04:56.922
So, that way, I don't
have to deal with

04:56.922 --> 04:59.508
the warping issues that comes
along with mild steel.

04:59.508 --> 05:01.426
My plan going forward
is just to set the forge-welds

05:01.426 --> 05:03.804
and see what I can do with
the amount of steel I have.

05:03.804 --> 05:05.388
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:05.388 --> 05:06.890
- I don't see
that any of our smiths

05:06.890 --> 05:08.850
have harvested
enough material

05:08.850 --> 05:11.102
to get a 10- to 13-inch blade.

05:11.102 --> 05:15.106
- The big hurdle to overcome
is having enough steel.

05:15.106 --> 05:17.108
- Right, so either
supplement it

05:17.108 --> 05:19.319
with some scrap material
out of our bin

05:19.319 --> 05:21.279
or go straight
and make a can.

05:21.279 --> 05:23.949
- I took
the high-carbon steel,

05:23.949 --> 05:26.785
and I cut it
into 12 4-inch pieces.

05:26.785 --> 05:28.995
<i>My goal is to take</i>
<i>that billet,</i>

05:28.995 --> 05:31.039
<i>get a good weld,</i>
<i>draw it out,</i>

05:31.039 --> 05:33.875
<i>and then forge-weld</i>
<i>the mild steel onto that</i>

05:33.875 --> 05:36.253
and hopefully get a san mai.

05:36.253 --> 05:39.631
<i>This is not a technique</i>
<i>that I would normally do,</i>

05:39.631 --> 05:41.675
but I needed to add
some thickness

05:41.675 --> 05:44.094
to this billet so I have a
little more metal to work with.

05:44.094 --> 05:47.472
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:47.472 --> 05:49.099
<i>- The first thing that comes</i>
<i>to mind</i>

05:49.099 --> 05:50.851
is that I know I'm gonna have
to forge-weld.

05:50.851 --> 05:52.519
<i>Forge-welding</i>
<i>is not something</i>

05:52.519 --> 05:54.229
<i>that I have a bunch</i>
<i>of experience in.</i>

05:54.229 --> 05:56.022
- Jason and Rob look
like they're going

05:56.022 --> 05:58.316
for that mild steel
san mai technique.

05:58.316 --> 06:00.026
- I think it'd be
a great technique,

06:00.026 --> 06:01.945
'cause then you have
that cushion on the sides

06:01.945 --> 06:04.364
of your blades--
acts like a shock absorber.

06:04.364 --> 06:07.033
<i>- My game plan is three layers</i>
<i>of hardenable down the middle</i>

06:07.033 --> 06:09.452
and two layers of mild steel
on the outside

06:09.452 --> 06:11.705
so that I can get
the thickness that I need.

06:11.705 --> 06:13.582
<i>My plan doesn't have</i>
<i>very many layers</i>

06:13.582 --> 06:15.542
<i>because that gives me</i>
<i>fewer opportunities</i>

06:15.542 --> 06:17.294
to screw up the forge-weld.
[chuckles]

06:17.294 --> 06:19.212
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:19.212 --> 06:21.715
<i>- Game plan right now</i>
<i>is to laminate together</i>

06:21.715 --> 06:23.842
<i>all the different layers</i>
<i>of steel that we have,</i>

06:23.842 --> 06:25.343
compressing it all
into one piece,

06:25.343 --> 06:27.220
and I'm gonna forge
out of that piece.

06:27.220 --> 06:29.055
<i>With the amount of metal</i>
<i>available to me,</i>

06:29.055 --> 06:30.932
<i>I'm just wondering</i>
<i>in the back of my mind,</i>

06:30.932 --> 06:32.517
"Is this really gonna be
enough steel

06:32.517 --> 06:33.852
to achieve the knife
I want to achieve?"

06:33.852 --> 06:35.145
- I think these guys
are gonna find out

06:35.145 --> 06:36.688
that they don't have
enough steel.

06:36.688 --> 06:39.357
So is it okay
to forge out what you got

06:39.357 --> 06:41.818
and then say, "Well, okay,,
I'm gonna add more now"?

06:41.818 --> 06:44.571
- You can,
but the longer the piece gets,

06:44.571 --> 06:46.948
the more tricky
the forge-weld's gonna become.

06:46.948 --> 06:50.118
So it's better off doing it now
while it's a shorter stack.

06:50.118 --> 06:53.163
- You only have two hours
remaining to finish your work!

06:53.163 --> 06:55.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:55.206 --> 06:57.167
- See Rob's material?

06:57.167 --> 06:59.294
It's like paper thin
at this point.

06:59.294 --> 07:01.338
- Need to add mass to it.

07:01.338 --> 07:03.173
<i>- My forge-weld</i>
<i>is pretty good,</i>

07:03.173 --> 07:04.883
but I think I'm gonna be
a little thinner

07:04.883 --> 07:06.926
than I want to be.

07:06.926 --> 07:09.638
<i>I need to add some more</i>
<i>mild steel to this billet.</i>

07:09.638 --> 07:12.515
- Rob's adding more steel
to his blade.

07:12.515 --> 07:14.684
<i>- I feel like</i>
<i>this is gonna work.</i>

07:14.684 --> 07:17.270
We'll find out.

07:17.270 --> 07:19.981
About two years
into my sickness,

07:19.981 --> 07:21.733
I nearly wasn't here.

07:21.733 --> 07:23.360
<i>I don't quit.</i>

07:23.360 --> 07:25.904
<i>You can ask my wife</i>
<i>and my children.</i>

07:25.904 --> 07:28.698
They'll tell you exactly
how hardheaded I am.

07:28.698 --> 07:30.116
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:30.116 --> 07:32.494
- All right.
- Sticking?

07:32.494 --> 07:35.163
- It looks like Jason's billet
is sticking together.

07:35.163 --> 07:37.290
- Looking good, man.

07:37.290 --> 07:38.833
- Hammering a little bit
of a tip in here, right?

07:38.833 --> 07:41.169
- Guess who's got it.

07:41.169 --> 07:43.505
<i>- Solid--</i>
<i>there's no weld lines.</i>

07:43.505 --> 07:44.714
Everything's clean
and good to go.

07:44.714 --> 07:49.928
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:49.928 --> 07:52.013
- Over here,
Michael is on the press--

07:52.013 --> 07:54.683
a very lean blade,

07:54.683 --> 07:56.309
and it looks like he's gonna go

07:56.309 --> 07:58.770
for a hidden tang
to conserve steel.

07:58.770 --> 08:00.689
- Smart move.

08:00.689 --> 08:02.607
- I'm finally getting it out
to a decent thickness,

08:02.607 --> 08:04.859
and my next step is to go
right to the quench.

08:04.859 --> 08:08.613
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:08.613 --> 08:11.032
- Michael has just quenched
his blade.

08:11.032 --> 08:12.909
- Quench early.
- Yep.

08:12.909 --> 08:14.994
- Doesn't hurt the blade.
You can grind a quenched blade.

08:14.994 --> 08:17.080
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:17.080 --> 08:19.749
- I quench the blade
before I do any kind of bevels,

08:19.749 --> 08:22.794
<i>because having the tons</i>
<i>of layers of steel in there,</i>

08:22.794 --> 08:24.337
<i>if it warps</i>
<i>you can grind it out.</i>

08:24.337 --> 08:25.755
All righty.

08:25.755 --> 08:28.591
Yeah, no warps.

08:28.591 --> 08:30.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:30.719 --> 08:33.054
<i>- Basically halfway through</i>
<i>my forge-welding process,</i>

08:33.054 --> 08:34.764
<i>and I realize, "I don't have</i>
<i>enough steel here.</i>

08:34.764 --> 08:36.266
This is gonna be a long knife."

08:36.266 --> 08:37.976
<i>And so, in the back</i>
<i>of my mind,</i>

08:37.976 --> 08:40.103
I'm also thinking,
"Do I add more layers,

08:40.103 --> 08:41.688
or do I try to work
with what I have?"

08:41.688 --> 08:43.440
<i>If I just use</i>
<i>this billet and I try</i>

08:43.440 --> 08:44.941
<i>to draw it out into a knife,</i>

08:44.941 --> 08:47.569
then I'll risk warping
or cracking.

08:47.569 --> 08:50.530
- Looks like Ryan
is welding that mild steel

08:50.530 --> 08:52.282
onto the outside of his billet.

08:52.282 --> 08:54.034
<i>- I've decided to add</i>
<i>some more layers.</i>

08:54.034 --> 08:55.702
There's plenty
of mild steel available.

08:55.702 --> 08:57.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:57.662 --> 08:59.622
This is essentially gonna act
as a san mai billet.

08:59.622 --> 09:01.374
Coming to the press.

09:01.374 --> 09:04.210
- Ryan's setting
that next set of welds.

09:04.210 --> 09:05.462
- [bleep].

09:05.462 --> 09:07.172
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:07.172 --> 09:08.882
Some of the pieces
are heating unevenly,

09:08.882 --> 09:10.425
<i>and I realize I have</i>
<i>a few delaminations</i>

09:10.425 --> 09:11.551
<i>in the outer layers.</i>

09:11.551 --> 09:13.053
[bleep].

09:13.053 --> 09:15.680
- Oh, boy.
- Oh, that's not good.

09:15.680 --> 09:17.682
<i>- My heart sinks.</i>

09:17.682 --> 09:20.727
The worst-case scenario
is that my outer layers fail.

09:20.727 --> 09:22.437
<i>That would be a real problem</i>

09:22.437 --> 09:24.731
<i>because I don't have time</i>
<i>to restart.</i>

09:24.731 --> 09:26.288
♪ ♪

09:28.818 --> 09:30.612
- Some of the pieces
are heating unevenly,

09:30.612 --> 09:31.946
<i>and I realize</i>
<i>I have a few delaminations</i>

09:31.946 --> 09:33.656
<i>in the outer layers.</i>

09:33.656 --> 09:35.116
[bleep].

09:35.116 --> 09:37.160
- Oh, boy.
- Oh, that's not good.

09:37.160 --> 09:40.163
- Worst-case scenario
is that my outer layers fail

09:40.163 --> 09:42.749
and that I've essentially
wasted that extra step.

09:42.749 --> 09:46.503
But I'm realizing
that I can grind off the bits

09:46.503 --> 09:48.254
that are delaminated.

09:48.254 --> 09:50.131
<i>The delaminations</i>
<i>are only at the ends</i>

09:50.131 --> 09:52.050
and only in the sides
of the billet.

09:52.050 --> 09:53.551
<i>The core steel is still good.</i>

09:53.551 --> 09:55.845
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:55.845 --> 09:58.181
- Jason's set up on
the flat platen over there.

09:58.181 --> 10:00.350
He has a thinner blade

10:00.350 --> 10:03.353
than most
of our other smiths out here.

10:03.353 --> 10:06.564
- When it gets
that thin at this point,

10:06.564 --> 10:08.817
I think you just do
an edge quench.

10:08.817 --> 10:10.819
Forget about the rest.
- Be a good idea.

10:10.819 --> 10:12.987
- It won't warp that way.

10:12.987 --> 10:14.447
- Here we go.

10:14.447 --> 10:16.574
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:16.574 --> 10:18.576
- Oh, crap.

10:18.576 --> 10:20.036
- Little bit
of a twist, I think.

10:20.036 --> 10:21.955
- Yep.

10:21.955 --> 10:24.457
Do it again.
[chuckles]

10:24.457 --> 10:26.167
I'd let the knife get
too cool to straighten it.

10:26.167 --> 10:27.877
So I'm gonna have to go back
in the forge.

10:27.877 --> 10:29.671
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:29.671 --> 10:32.465
- Jason's in the quench again.

10:32.465 --> 10:34.217
- Don't be stupid on me now.

10:34.217 --> 10:35.802
- Still twisted.

10:35.802 --> 10:37.846
- [grunts]

10:37.846 --> 10:39.305
<i>You know they say insanity</i>
<i>is doing the same thing</i>

10:39.305 --> 10:40.807
over and over again

10:40.807 --> 10:42.308
and expecting
a different result.

10:42.308 --> 10:43.560
But I'm gonna try it
a third time.

10:43.560 --> 10:50.191
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:50.191 --> 10:51.776
<i>I'm still crooked.</i>

10:51.776 --> 10:54.404
So I know at this point,
it is what it is.

10:54.404 --> 10:57.240
I've got to get it as clean
and straight as I can.

10:57.240 --> 11:00.743
Crooked as crap,
but hard.

11:00.743 --> 11:03.663
- Michael has a quenched,
hardened blade right now.

11:03.663 --> 11:07.500
For the last hour, he's just
been refining his blade shape.

11:07.500 --> 11:09.669
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:09.669 --> 11:12.630
<i>- My hands and neck are trying</i>
<i>to cramp up very bad.</i>

11:12.630 --> 11:14.924
I'm feeling like
Mr. Crab Hands over here.

11:14.924 --> 11:18.553
So I get a banana to help
with the cramping.

11:18.553 --> 11:21.472
Me being Spicy Mike, I got to
dump hot sauce all over it.

11:21.472 --> 11:23.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:23.641 --> 11:25.768
- 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

11:25.768 --> 11:29.063
You have 30 minutes
to finish your banana

11:29.063 --> 11:30.398
and finish your blade!

11:30.398 --> 11:32.609
[laughter]

11:32.609 --> 11:35.195
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.195 --> 11:38.865
<i>- I've still not got the blade</i>
<i>up to temperature to harden.</i>

11:38.865 --> 11:40.658
I've got one shot at this.

11:40.658 --> 11:43.578
If this blade, warps, cracks,
anything, I am done.

11:43.578 --> 11:45.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:45.955 --> 11:47.123
- There's Rob in the oil.

11:47.123 --> 11:49.209
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:49.209 --> 11:51.920
- [groans]
It's not--

11:51.920 --> 11:53.588
A little bit of a warp.

11:53.588 --> 11:56.299
So I put it in
the vise real quick.

11:56.299 --> 11:58.092
- This guy is not a small dude,

11:58.092 --> 11:59.594
putting a lot of weight on
that blade.

11:59.594 --> 12:01.429
I'm worried about it.

12:01.429 --> 12:03.348
- As straight
as it's gonna get today.

12:03.348 --> 12:05.808
- 15 minutes, bladesmiths!

12:05.808 --> 12:08.519
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:08.519 --> 12:10.647
<i>- I have the edge</i>
<i>where I want it,</i>

12:10.647 --> 12:12.732
<i>and that's where I'm noticing</i>
<i>that the delaminations</i>

12:12.732 --> 12:14.400
<i>that I noticed earlier</i>
<i>are running</i>

12:14.400 --> 12:16.945
significantly deeper
than I initially thought.

12:16.945 --> 12:19.405
<i>But I'm not overly concerned</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

12:19.405 --> 12:21.199
- Oh, look at that.
Look at that.

12:21.199 --> 12:24.077
Ryan just peeled back
a piece of steel on his blade.

12:24.077 --> 12:25.912
- Whoop.
- Oh, dude.

12:25.912 --> 12:27.288
You got plenty
of mass, though.

12:27.288 --> 12:29.040
- Oh, yeah,
I'm not even worried at all.

12:29.040 --> 12:30.208
It's like, whoop, whoop, whoop,
whoop, whoop.

12:30.208 --> 12:31.751
- [laughing]

12:31.751 --> 12:33.294
- He's showing Mike
like it's a joke,

12:33.294 --> 12:35.004
but this is a serious problem.

12:35.004 --> 12:37.757
- Yeah. At least it's
on the tang, though.

12:37.757 --> 12:40.051
- Hopefully it doesn't travel
further up into the blade.

12:40.051 --> 12:41.886
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:41.886 --> 12:43.554
- The heat treat is going to be

12:43.554 --> 12:45.682
what makes or breaks
the blade, very literally.

12:45.682 --> 12:47.350
<i>This is when I'll find</i>
<i>out whether or not</i>

12:47.350 --> 12:49.811
<i>those de-welded issues</i>
<i>are gonna show up.</i>

12:49.811 --> 12:51.145
Whoo!

12:51.145 --> 12:52.855
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:52.855 --> 12:54.983
Ha ha!

12:54.983 --> 12:56.192
<i>The knife looks straight.</i>

12:56.192 --> 12:57.902
Whoo-whee!

12:57.902 --> 12:59.112
<i>I know there are some</i>
<i>surface issues,</i>

12:59.112 --> 13:00.697
but this hardening
has proved

13:00.697 --> 13:02.615
that those issues
are just surface issues.

13:02.615 --> 13:05.034
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:05.034 --> 13:08.788
- Ten, nine, eight, seven,

13:08.788 --> 13:11.958
six, five, four,

13:11.958 --> 13:15.003
three, two, one.

13:15.003 --> 13:16.296
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

13:16.296 --> 13:17.755
Drop your tools!

13:17.755 --> 13:20.341
This first round of competition
is over!

13:20.341 --> 13:22.010
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:22.010 --> 13:23.428
<i>- So I'm looking</i>
<i>at my blade</i>

13:23.428 --> 13:24.971
<i>knowing I've done</i>
<i>the best I can.</i>

13:24.971 --> 13:26.973
I'm gonna throw up a prayer.

13:26.973 --> 13:29.475
I don't know if God cares about
"Forged in Fire" or not,

13:29.475 --> 13:31.477
but I know He cares about me,
so I'm gonna give it a shot.

13:31.477 --> 13:33.771
[laughs]

13:33.771 --> 13:36.899
- Well, bladesmiths,
that first round of competition

13:36.899 --> 13:39.569
seemed to go smooth
as Tennessee whiskey.

13:39.569 --> 13:41.070
Now it's time for the judges

13:41.070 --> 13:42.780
to take a closer look
at your work.

13:42.780 --> 13:44.323
Rob, you're up first.

13:44.323 --> 13:46.200
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:46.200 --> 13:47.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:47.952 --> 13:49.579
<i>- Rob, I really like</i>
<i>the shape,</i>

13:49.579 --> 13:51.748
but I'm assuming
your hands

13:51.748 --> 13:53.499
are quite a bit larger
than mine.

13:53.499 --> 13:55.418
Yeah, that's what I figured.

13:55.418 --> 13:58.588
There's just probably
an extra inch of handle there.

13:58.588 --> 14:01.466
If I were you,
I would definitely deal

14:01.466 --> 14:03.051
with these delams,
especially the ones

14:03.051 --> 14:05.470
down here low on the blade.

14:05.470 --> 14:07.930
- Jason, please present
your work to the judges.

14:07.930 --> 14:09.974
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:09.974 --> 14:12.018
<i>- Jason, I think you win</i>
<i>the award</i>

14:12.018 --> 14:13.978
<i>for the biggest curve in</i>
<i>a knife I've seen this season.</i>

14:13.978 --> 14:15.772
That sucker's got quite
a bend to it.

14:15.772 --> 14:18.524
But if you carefully apply heat

14:18.524 --> 14:20.234
in the spots you need to
on this blade,

14:20.234 --> 14:22.153
you should be able
to straighten everything out.

14:22.153 --> 14:24.530
Your handle doesn't have
a lot of contour

14:24.530 --> 14:27.200
in the back end,
but good job.

14:27.200 --> 14:28.659
- All right, Jason, first up,

14:28.659 --> 14:30.745
I like the shape
of your blade here.

14:30.745 --> 14:33.831
On your blade itself,
there's really no delaminations

14:33.831 --> 14:35.500
or issues that I see with it.

14:35.500 --> 14:36.501
Good job.

14:36.501 --> 14:38.086
- Michael, you're up.

14:38.086 --> 14:39.962
Please present your work
to the judges.

14:39.962 --> 14:41.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:41.756 --> 14:44.008
<i>- Other than these</i>
<i>funny little delams</i>

14:44.008 --> 14:45.927
<i>right up here,</i>
<i>your steel looks fantastic.</i>

14:45.927 --> 14:49.931
I'm a huge fan of hidden
and through tang construction.

14:49.931 --> 14:53.309
I really like the fact
that you got a well-ground,

14:53.309 --> 14:55.686
almost finished-looking blade.

14:55.686 --> 14:57.396
- Ryan, you're up.

14:57.396 --> 14:58.856
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:58.856 --> 15:01.067
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:01.067 --> 15:03.778
<i>- First off, I like the whole</i>
<i>competition cutter thing.</i>

15:03.778 --> 15:05.279
<i>One thing I'm concerned</i>
<i>about is all</i>

15:05.279 --> 15:06.989
these delaminations here.

15:06.989 --> 15:09.367
I mean,
I can get my fingernails

15:09.367 --> 15:10.993
under a lot of these,

15:10.993 --> 15:13.746
and they're going
all the way down here.

15:13.746 --> 15:16.207
Gives me the impression
that more of this

15:16.207 --> 15:17.959
isn't forge-welded together.

15:17.959 --> 15:20.002
So that's a big concern.

15:20.002 --> 15:22.880
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:22.880 --> 15:25.800
- Bladesmiths, the judges have
evaluated your work,

15:25.800 --> 15:28.052
and it's time for one of you
to leave The Forge.

15:28.052 --> 15:34.684
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:34.684 --> 15:36.144
- Ryan...

15:36.144 --> 15:38.521
your blade did not
make the cut.

15:38.521 --> 15:40.606
- Yeah, Ryan,
with all those delaminations,

15:40.606 --> 15:42.441
<i>it's really questionable</i>

15:42.441 --> 15:44.110
whether you could fix those
on the grinder or not.

15:44.110 --> 15:45.987
That being said,
you've also got the most work

15:45.987 --> 15:48.239
of any of the other smiths
to try to correct your issues.

15:48.239 --> 15:50.366
That's why
we're sending you home.

15:50.366 --> 15:52.201
- Ryan, you did amazing work.

15:52.201 --> 15:53.661
Unfortunately,
I have to ask you

15:53.661 --> 15:55.371
to please surrender your blade.

15:55.371 --> 15:56.706
<i>- I'm tempted</i>
<i>to be disappointed,</i>

15:56.706 --> 15:58.708
<i>and I'm tempted to be upset.</i>

15:58.708 --> 16:01.335
This is definitely not an ideal
situation to have been in.

16:01.335 --> 16:02.920
<i>I used all the time allotted.</i>

16:02.920 --> 16:04.714
I think I worked
as efficiently as I could,

16:04.714 --> 16:06.215
but I definitely wish
that I could have done more

16:06.215 --> 16:07.758
to address some
of these issues.

16:07.758 --> 16:10.178
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:10.178 --> 16:12.138
- Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

16:12.138 --> 16:14.849
Your work has earned you
a spot in the second round.

16:14.849 --> 16:16.684
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

16:16.684 --> 16:19.312
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons.

16:19.312 --> 16:21.772
In the first round, you used
metal from that whiskey barrel

16:21.772 --> 16:24.066
to forge your blades
in your signature style.

16:24.066 --> 16:26.736
Now your handles
must be made

16:26.736 --> 16:30.448
from the same whiskey barrel
that you made your blades from.

16:30.448 --> 16:32.700
You'll have three hours
in this round.

16:32.700 --> 16:34.785
At the end of this round,
your blades will be tested

16:34.785 --> 16:36.287
for strength and durability

16:36.287 --> 16:38.706
in a whiskey barrel ring chop

16:38.706 --> 16:41.417
and for edge retention
in an apple slice.

16:41.417 --> 16:43.002
Good luck, bladesmiths.

16:43.002 --> 16:44.670
Your three hours starts...

16:44.670 --> 16:46.047
now.

16:46.047 --> 16:49.258
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:49.258 --> 16:51.761
So all the scales
for the bulk of the handle,

16:51.761 --> 16:53.346
they have to use
the wood from the barrel.

16:53.346 --> 16:55.014
- Right.

16:55.014 --> 16:56.682
- Michael's grabbing those
barrel staves,

16:56.682 --> 16:58.976
the sides of the barrel--
those are curved.

16:58.976 --> 17:00.645
I mean, you're gonna have
better slab material

17:00.645 --> 17:02.313
with the top or
the bottom of the barrel

17:02.313 --> 17:03.314
'cause it's already flat.

17:03.314 --> 17:05.107
- Yeah, it's thicker too.

17:05.107 --> 17:07.777
<i>- The judges said</i>
<i>my handle was too long.</i>

17:07.777 --> 17:09.612
<i>So I need to shorten it</i>

17:09.612 --> 17:11.739
and then worry
about getting

17:11.739 --> 17:13.824
the handle material
from the barrel.

17:13.824 --> 17:16.494
- You know, Rob has just cut
a section off the back

17:16.494 --> 17:18.496
of his tang over
on the chop saw.

17:18.496 --> 17:20.289
Now he's welding the flare back
on, so that's good to see.

17:20.289 --> 17:21.916
- Shortened it up some,
took an inch or so

17:21.916 --> 17:24.168
of material out of there--
it's a good idea.

17:24.168 --> 17:26.087
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:26.087 --> 17:27.713
<i>- I'm really not happy</i>
<i>with the things</i>

17:27.713 --> 17:29.382
<i>in my blade</i>
<i>the judges pointed out.</i>

17:29.382 --> 17:30.925
First thing I've got
to do with my knife

17:30.925 --> 17:32.843
is deal
with the warpage issue.

17:32.843 --> 17:34.720
- I find it exciting
watching him heat it,

17:34.720 --> 17:36.097
try and bend it by hand
in the vise--

17:36.097 --> 17:37.682
very entertaining.

17:37.682 --> 17:40.059
- Waiting for that... tink.
- Snap.

17:40.059 --> 17:41.978
- Sometimes it's stressful
putting pressure

17:41.978 --> 17:44.397
on a blade sideways,
but this is a technique

17:44.397 --> 17:46.816
I've used lots of times before.

17:46.816 --> 17:48.901
There it was.

17:48.901 --> 17:50.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:50.987 --> 17:52.822
- Michael's gonna have
a little bit tougher time,

17:52.822 --> 17:55.366
having a hidden tang,
if he's going through.

17:55.366 --> 17:57.743
But there's definitely
enough material there.

17:57.743 --> 17:59.912
<i>- So I don't normally make</i>
<i>hidden-tang knives.</i>

17:59.912 --> 18:01.747
I'm not really a fan of them.

18:01.747 --> 18:05.543
<i>I do full tang mostly,</i>
<i>and it's way simpler,</i>

18:05.543 --> 18:08.379
in terms of overall steps
to finish the product.

18:08.379 --> 18:10.423
I've got three hours to put
the handle on a knife.

18:10.423 --> 18:12.425
It seems pretty simple.

18:12.425 --> 18:14.385
- One hour has elapsed!

18:14.385 --> 18:18.014
You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work!

18:18.014 --> 18:22.226
- Finish grinding, and now
it's time for the wood handles.

18:22.226 --> 18:24.020
<i>It's a whiskey barrel,</i>
<i>so you're going to have</i>

18:24.020 --> 18:27.106
to try to find a flat area
to get your pieces from

18:27.106 --> 18:28.983
because then you're gonna have
to get on the grinder

18:28.983 --> 18:30.985
<i>to make them flat.</i>

18:30.985 --> 18:32.862
- Now, what about
the structural integrity

18:32.862 --> 18:34.530
of the wood
in the barrel itself.

18:34.530 --> 18:36.616
I mean,
how tough is this stuff?

18:36.616 --> 18:39.035
- I don't know, it works
very well in "Donkey Kong,"

18:39.035 --> 18:41.245
so it must be strong stuff.
[laughter]

18:41.245 --> 18:43.289
- I'm pretty sure it's gonna
make a decent handle.

18:43.289 --> 18:47.293
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:47.293 --> 18:49.879
- The judges pointed out some
things wrong with my blade--

18:49.879 --> 18:51.839
<i>particularly</i>
<i>the handle being small.</i>

18:51.839 --> 18:54.091
So my plan is to cut
the end of my blade off

18:54.091 --> 18:57.178
and weld on a new piece
of metal to rebuild the handle.

18:57.178 --> 18:59.263
So I'm gonna weld
on some mild steel.

18:59.263 --> 19:01.349
All that's gonna be covered
safely by the scales.

19:01.349 --> 19:02.892
Shouldn't have
any strength issues.

19:02.892 --> 19:04.727
That'll give me the chance

19:04.727 --> 19:06.520
to correct the handle-geometry
problem that I had.

19:06.520 --> 19:09.482
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:09.482 --> 19:11.108
<i>- The judges were really</i>
<i>pleased with the fact</i>

19:11.108 --> 19:12.818
<i>that I went with</i>
<i>a hidden-tang knife.</i>

19:12.818 --> 19:16.364
But I'm trying to get it
to fit inside the wood handle.

19:16.364 --> 19:18.532
And I start panicking.

19:18.532 --> 19:20.409
That doesn't work.
Got it.

19:20.409 --> 19:22.370
<i>My only option is really</i>
<i>to cut off the tang</i>

19:22.370 --> 19:24.121
to meet the depth
of the drill bit.

19:24.121 --> 19:25.539
- Don't do it.
Don't do it.

19:25.539 --> 19:26.957
- I just don't get it.

19:26.957 --> 19:29.168
I don't understand...
- Oh, , my God.

19:29.168 --> 19:32.088
Why smiths continuously take
material off the tang,

19:32.088 --> 19:33.839
when it's really easy
to drill wood.

19:33.839 --> 19:35.883
- I just feel overwhelmed--

19:35.883 --> 19:37.927
like, that I'm just not gonna
have enough time to finish.

19:37.927 --> 19:40.221
- Structurally you want
that tang to go

19:40.221 --> 19:41.847
at least three quarters
of the way through

19:41.847 --> 19:43.265
that handle material.

19:43.265 --> 19:45.101
At this rate,
instead of having a tang

19:45.101 --> 19:47.353
that's going to be stable,
going through most

19:47.353 --> 19:48.854
of the handle material,
we're gonna have a thumbtack

19:48.854 --> 19:49.772
on the end.

19:52.191 --> 19:53.818
- The tang looks
a little shorter
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:53.818 --> 19:55.611
than I really want it
to right now,

19:55.611 --> 19:58.197
but I just need to get
it together so it can compete.

19:58.197 --> 20:00.408
- Michael's gone back
to the grinder,

20:00.408 --> 20:04.495
and he keeps just "auging" away
steel off of this tang.

20:04.495 --> 20:06.330
- It's like thinning out
the bones in your legs

20:06.330 --> 20:08.165
and then trying
to run a marathon.

20:08.165 --> 20:09.917
- Damn it.

20:09.917 --> 20:11.585
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:11.585 --> 20:13.337
<i>- So I've got</i>
<i>my scales glued on.</i>

20:13.337 --> 20:15.089
I have to get
this handle shaped,

20:15.089 --> 20:17.258
slicked up where
it feels good in the hand,

20:17.258 --> 20:19.969
and then go back
and get on my blade

20:19.969 --> 20:21.971
<i>and get my blade sharp.</i>

20:21.971 --> 20:25.933
<i>Well, my height is</i>
<i>a disadvantage at times.</i>

20:25.933 --> 20:28.644
- Rob's got the squat position
going now.

20:28.644 --> 20:31.480
I've seen smiths put boxes
under there to stand on.

20:31.480 --> 20:33.858
I've seen smiths climb
on the table,

20:33.858 --> 20:35.192
but I've never seen--
that's the first smith--

20:35.192 --> 20:37.069
- You've never seen
the half squat?

20:37.069 --> 20:39.530
- First smith we had squat
over to work on the machine.

20:39.530 --> 20:41.574
<i>- I'm used to having to adapt.</i>

20:41.574 --> 20:44.326
<i>I'm 6'5", and so</i>
<i>I'm hitting my head</i>

20:44.326 --> 20:46.120
all the time
on something, so...

20:46.120 --> 20:47.705
Yeah, you get used to it.

20:47.705 --> 20:50.124
- 30 minutes remaining
to finish your work!

20:50.124 --> 20:53.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:53.377 --> 20:55.838
- I pull the knife out of
the vise after the glue is dry.

20:55.838 --> 20:58.215
<i>And there's a big old ugly gap</i>
<i>on the end.</i>

20:58.215 --> 21:00.217
Little gappy.

21:00.217 --> 21:02.511
The first thing I try to do is
fill it with something.

21:02.511 --> 21:04.513
<i>I'm gonna try super glue</i>
<i>and wood dust,</i>

21:04.513 --> 21:06.265
<i>see if I can maybe get it</i>
<i>to blend in.</i>

21:06.265 --> 21:08.934
- Jason's using
a lot of Krazy Glue filler.

21:08.934 --> 21:10.686
<i>- I can't really find</i>
<i>any dust</i>

21:10.686 --> 21:12.396
<i>because they've got good dust</i>
<i>collection here.</i>

21:12.396 --> 21:15.065
So I have to apply
the glue while I'm grinding

21:15.065 --> 21:16.776
<i>so that the dust</i>
<i>will go into the gap.</i>

21:16.776 --> 21:18.319
That'll work.

21:18.319 --> 21:20.404
- Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

21:20.404 --> 21:23.699
You have just ten minutes
remaining to finish your...

21:23.699 --> 21:24.909
bananas.

21:24.909 --> 21:26.869
- [laughs]

21:26.869 --> 21:28.329
You guys need hot sauce on it.

21:28.329 --> 21:29.914
- No hot sauce.

21:29.914 --> 21:31.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:31.582 --> 21:33.292
<i>- The tang didn't quite</i>
<i>friction fit</i>

21:33.292 --> 21:35.211
<i>like I wanted it to.</i>

21:35.211 --> 21:37.129
<i>But I think I'm gonna be</i>
<i>all right with it.</i>

21:37.129 --> 21:39.089
So now that everything is
actually together,

21:39.089 --> 21:41.091
<i>all I have to do</i>
<i>is minor finish work,</i>

21:41.091 --> 21:43.135
<i>and I'm really starting</i>
<i>to calm down.</i>

21:43.135 --> 21:45.262
I know that I'm gonna make it.

21:45.262 --> 21:47.932
- Ten, nine, eight,

21:47.932 --> 21:51.769
seven, six, five, four,

21:51.769 --> 21:54.855
three, two, one.

21:54.855 --> 21:56.440
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

21:56.440 --> 21:57.983
Drop your tools.

21:57.983 --> 21:59.443
This round is over.

21:59.443 --> 22:00.986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:00.986 --> 22:02.738
<i>- I'm extremely happy.</i>

22:02.738 --> 22:04.198
For having to throw
this together

22:04.198 --> 22:06.408
in a total of six hours,

22:06.408 --> 22:09.495
<i>I think this is one of the</i>
<i>better knives I've ever made.</i>

22:09.495 --> 22:12.748
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to our strength test--

22:12.748 --> 22:14.959
the whiskey barrel ring chop.

22:14.959 --> 22:16.627
Now, I'm gonna take each
of your knives,

22:16.627 --> 22:18.838
and I'm gonna beat them
repeatedly and viciously

22:18.838 --> 22:20.798
into these
whiskey barrel rings.

22:20.798 --> 22:23.342
I don't really care what
your knives do to the rings.

22:23.342 --> 22:25.135
I want to see what the rings
are gonna do to your knives.

22:25.135 --> 22:26.846
Rob, you're first.

22:26.846 --> 22:28.430
Ready to go?
- Go for it.

22:28.430 --> 22:30.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:30.641 --> 22:32.977
<i>This is a real test</i>
<i>of the heat treat.</i>

22:32.977 --> 22:36.021
<i>If your heat treat's not on</i>
<i>in this test,</i>

22:36.021 --> 22:37.815
you're gonna suffer some damage
to your blade.

22:37.815 --> 22:44.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.572 --> 22:47.992
- [grunting]

22:47.992 --> 22:53.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:56.000 --> 22:57.626
- It's still in one piece.

22:57.626 --> 23:01.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:01.255 --> 23:03.048
- Well, Rob,
we took a little damage.

23:03.048 --> 23:04.842
I mean,
we're biting into

23:04.842 --> 23:06.760
that ring quite well,

23:06.760 --> 23:09.847
but we did leave
a piece of it in the ring.

23:09.847 --> 23:11.724
But this is definitely
stronger than

23:11.724 --> 23:13.517
the steel you made it from.

23:13.517 --> 23:15.728
Good job.
- Thank you.

23:15.728 --> 23:17.646
- How you feeling now, Jason?

23:17.646 --> 23:19.481
- I'm interested to see
how mine will perform.

23:19.481 --> 23:21.025
- We're all gonna find
out together.

23:21.025 --> 23:27.907
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:35.581 --> 23:38.792
- [grunting]

23:38.792 --> 23:41.253
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:41.253 --> 23:43.172
- [exhales sharply, chuckles]

23:43.172 --> 23:44.757
- Dude, that was--
- Man.

23:44.757 --> 23:47.217
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.217 --> 23:49.803
- Jason,
very good job on the blade.

23:49.803 --> 23:51.639
You got a little chipping
and edge rolling,

23:51.639 --> 23:53.140
but it's really not
much of anything,

23:53.140 --> 23:55.684
considering what
I just did to that ring.

23:55.684 --> 23:58.103
The one problem I have
is your handle.

23:58.103 --> 24:01.774
It's very narrow and rounded,

24:01.774 --> 24:04.652
but overall nicely done.

24:04.652 --> 24:06.862
Michael, you ready to go?

24:06.862 --> 24:08.155
- It's gonna hurt worse
than hot sauce

24:08.155 --> 24:09.448
watching you smash by baby.

24:09.448 --> 24:10.908
- [chuckles]

24:10.908 --> 24:17.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:25.089 --> 24:28.550
[grunting]

24:28.550 --> 24:33.973
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:33.973 --> 24:36.225
- That hurts so bad.
[laughs]

24:36.225 --> 24:39.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:39.311 --> 24:40.854
- Congratulations, Michael

24:40.854 --> 24:43.023
Blade held up well.
- [sighs]

24:43.023 --> 24:44.483
- We got a little chipping.

24:44.483 --> 24:46.318
Got a couple little spots
that are missing.

24:46.318 --> 24:48.696
The other thing is
if I didn't have a glove on,

24:48.696 --> 24:50.197
I'd be feeling these corners.

24:50.197 --> 24:53.117
But overall nice job.

24:53.117 --> 24:56.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:56.495 --> 24:57.997
- Next up is
the sharpness test,

24:57.997 --> 24:59.999
a fan favorite,
the apple slice.

24:59.999 --> 25:02.960
This is all about what
your blades do to those apples.

25:02.960 --> 25:05.713
Good, sharp blade should pass
right through them.

25:05.713 --> 25:07.589
Rob, you're up first.
You ready?

25:07.589 --> 25:09.925
- Let's see what's left.
- Okay.

25:09.925 --> 25:12.469
<i>- There's part</i>
<i>of my baby still out there</i>

25:12.469 --> 25:14.388
in the floor somewhere,
so I'm feeling

25:14.388 --> 25:16.765
<i>a little saddened about that,</i>
<i>but if I can do well</i>

25:16.765 --> 25:19.435
on the apple slice,
it could bring me back.

25:19.435 --> 25:22.000
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:31.822 --> 25:33.782
- Yes.
[chuckles] Yeah.

25:33.782 --> 25:36.994
- Clean cuts right there.

25:36.994 --> 25:40.080
- So, Rob,
where you have an edge,

25:40.080 --> 25:41.665
it's very sharp.

25:41.665 --> 25:43.250
You can see
it picked up a lot

25:43.250 --> 25:45.335
of material right there
where the chip is,

25:45.335 --> 25:46.754
and that last apple
is standing.

25:46.754 --> 25:48.088
I just ran out of blade.

25:48.088 --> 25:50.632
It's cut halfway through.
Good job.

25:50.632 --> 25:52.384
All right, Jason,
you ready?

25:52.384 --> 25:54.303
- Yes, sir.

25:54.303 --> 25:57.806
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:57.806 --> 26:00.142
[exhales deeply]

26:00.142 --> 26:05.689
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:05.689 --> 26:08.484
- Oh, yeah.
I knew you had that.

26:08.484 --> 26:12.071
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:12.071 --> 26:14.323
- It's a big carving knife.

26:14.323 --> 26:16.617
The blade passed through
the apples nicely.

26:16.617 --> 26:18.577
Cracked a couple of them,
but you don't

26:18.577 --> 26:21.080
really see any marks left
by the tears

26:21.080 --> 26:22.539
that are in this blade.

26:22.539 --> 26:23.916
It's a good cutter.

26:23.916 --> 26:25.793
Well done.

26:25.793 --> 26:27.669
All right, Michael,
you ready?

26:27.669 --> 26:29.129
- Feeling saucy.

26:29.129 --> 26:31.340
- [chuckles]

26:31.340 --> 26:38.263
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:44.478 --> 26:46.230
Just catching
that last apple

26:46.230 --> 26:48.524
and cutting that clean
and that thin a slice

26:48.524 --> 26:50.859
off of it
shows a really sharp blade.

26:50.859 --> 26:53.362
Without the grinds going all
the way to the edge,

26:53.362 --> 26:55.656
it's sort of pushing
its way through.

26:55.656 --> 26:57.199
It's cutting three quarters
of the way through the apple

26:57.199 --> 26:58.575
and breaking
the rest of the way,

26:58.575 --> 27:00.452
just wedging it open.

27:00.452 --> 27:02.621
It's that wedge shape--
probably started riding up

27:02.621 --> 27:04.790
on that lower edge
and just climbed up

27:04.790 --> 27:06.333
out of those apples.

27:06.333 --> 27:08.252
But definitely a sharp knife.

27:08.252 --> 27:10.212
Good job.
- Thank you.

27:10.212 --> 27:12.714
- Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete.

27:12.714 --> 27:14.758
They've made a final decision.

27:14.758 --> 27:17.219
It's time for one of you
bladesmiths to leave The Forge.

27:17.219 --> 27:21.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:21.932 --> 27:25.727
Rob, your blade did not
make the cut.

27:25.727 --> 27:27.396
- Rob,
you brought us a knife

27:27.396 --> 27:29.439
that was beautifully designed

27:29.439 --> 27:31.525
with an incredibly
comfortable handle,

27:31.525 --> 27:32.943
which I really appreciate.

27:32.943 --> 27:34.486
Unfortunately,
in that strength test,

27:34.486 --> 27:35.863
you left about
an inch of your blade

27:35.863 --> 27:37.698
in that barrel strap.

27:37.698 --> 27:39.116
For that reason,
we're gonna have to let you go.

27:39.116 --> 27:41.076
- Fine.

27:41.076 --> 27:44.204
- Rob, please surrender
your blade.

27:44.204 --> 27:45.956
<i>- I came out to</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>

27:45.956 --> 27:48.000
to prove to myself
that I could still do this

27:48.000 --> 27:50.294
after the issues
I've had with my health,

27:50.294 --> 27:52.170
<i>and I performed.</i>

27:52.170 --> 27:54.423
It was very tough,
but I made it through.

27:54.423 --> 27:56.258
<i>My family, you know,</i>
<i>they had pushed me</i>

27:56.258 --> 27:57.926
<i>to come and try to do this.</i>

27:57.926 --> 27:59.469
I know they'll still be
proud of me.

27:59.469 --> 28:03.223
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:03.223 --> 28:05.267
- Jason, Michael,
congratulations.

28:05.267 --> 28:07.519
Your work has earned you
a spot in this finale.

28:07.519 --> 28:09.646
When you guys showed up here,
you used our forge

28:09.646 --> 28:13.025
and our equipment to make
blades out of barrels.

28:13.025 --> 28:15.152
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

28:15.152 --> 28:17.613
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

28:17.613 --> 28:18.989
That weapon is...

28:18.989 --> 28:22.075
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:22.075 --> 28:23.619
The qinglong ji.

28:23.619 --> 28:25.704
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:25.704 --> 28:28.040
<i>The qinglong ji is</i>
<i>a Chinese pole arm</i>

28:28.040 --> 28:29.833
<i>made famous during</i>
<i>the Han Dynasty</i>

28:29.833 --> 28:31.627
<i>in the 2nd century.</i>

28:31.627 --> 28:33.879
<i>Over six feet long,</i>
<i>the qinglong ji featured</i>

28:33.879 --> 28:36.173
<i>a fierce point for stabbing</i>
<i>and slashing.</i>

28:36.173 --> 28:38.175
<i>The crescent of the weapon</i>
<i>was equally dangerous</i>

28:38.175 --> 28:41.136
<i>and could be employed</i>
<i>to dismount oncoming cavalry</i>

28:41.136 --> 28:43.513
<i>or tear away enemy shields.</i>

28:43.513 --> 28:45.891
<i>A skilled user could also use</i>
<i>the crescent portion</i>

28:45.891 --> 28:48.060
<i>to ward off enemy attacks.</i>

28:48.060 --> 28:51.063
<i>However, the qinglong ji</i>
<i>was at its deadliest</i>

28:51.063 --> 28:52.564
<i>when employed en masse,</i>

28:52.564 --> 28:54.441
<i>creating</i>
<i>a terrifying spear wall</i>

28:54.441 --> 28:56.652
<i>that kept foes at a distance.</i>

28:56.652 --> 28:59.196
<i>The qinglong ji</i>
<i>is the famed weapon of Lu Bu.,</i>

28:59.196 --> 29:01.406
<i>legendary warrior featured</i>
<i>in the television series</i>

29:01.406 --> 29:03.533
"Three Kingdoms."

29:03.533 --> 29:05.661
The length of your double-wave,
double-edged blade

29:05.661 --> 29:10.374
at the top of this weapon must
be between 12 and 14 inches.

29:10.374 --> 29:13.543
The crescent blade must be
between 7 and 9 inches.

29:13.543 --> 29:16.630
And to top it all off,
you must include a butt cap

29:16.630 --> 29:18.465
on this weapon.

29:18.465 --> 29:20.258
You will have five days
at your home forge

29:20.258 --> 29:21.718
to complete this challenge.

29:21.718 --> 29:23.387
After five days,
you'll return

29:23.387 --> 29:25.347
with your weapons
and present them to our judges,

29:25.347 --> 29:27.724
who will test them thoroughly
and brutally.

29:27.724 --> 29:29.559
And only after
they've done that

29:29.559 --> 29:32.145
and inspected your work
will they declare one of you

29:32.145 --> 29:33.855
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

29:33.855 --> 29:35.649
who also leaves
with a check for 10 grand.

29:35.649 --> 29:37.109
Good luck, bladesmiths.

29:37.109 --> 29:39.111
We'll see you in five days.

29:40.737 --> 29:43.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:43.448 --> 29:45.283
<i>- I'm really glad to be home.</i>

29:45.283 --> 29:47.494
<i>I told myself going</i>
<i>into this competition</i>

29:47.494 --> 29:49.579
that if I can just make it to
the house, I'll be all right.

29:49.579 --> 29:51.540
<i>For day one,</i>
<i>what I'm planning on</i>

29:51.540 --> 29:53.625
is forging a billet
of Damascus

29:53.625 --> 29:56.670
and forging that into
the crescent blade

29:56.670 --> 29:59.047
that'll be alongside
of the qinglong ji.

29:59.047 --> 30:02.134
<i>Putting a twist in the billet</i>
<i>makes the pattern more bold.</i>

30:02.134 --> 30:04.845
<i>It gives me some angles</i>
<i>rather than just lines.</i>

30:04.845 --> 30:06.680
One of the things that makes
this shape hard

30:06.680 --> 30:08.557
<i>is that as you forge</i>
<i>the bevel,</i>

30:08.557 --> 30:11.893
the knife wants
to bend away from the edge.

30:11.893 --> 30:15.313
This crescent has to have
the knife inside the edge.

30:15.313 --> 30:19.151
This is a 33-layer twist
Damascus billet.

30:19.151 --> 30:22.654
I'm hoping the judges are gonna
appreciate my work.

30:22.654 --> 30:25.115
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:25.115 --> 30:27.451
<i>For day one,</i>
<i>got to make this shiny</i>

30:27.451 --> 30:30.746
spear thing,
and ready to get started.

30:30.746 --> 30:33.165
Khazum!

30:33.165 --> 30:36.126
So my plan for today is
to get as far as I can

30:36.126 --> 30:39.046
with the forging
of the main shaft of the blade.

30:39.046 --> 30:42.340
I'm betting it's at least
125 degrees in here,

30:42.340 --> 30:43.759
<i>if not closer to 130.</i>

30:43.759 --> 30:45.761
<i>But I've got this press,</i>

30:45.761 --> 30:48.263
<i>and it's gonna make</i>
<i>things way easier.</i>

30:48.263 --> 30:50.557
I could marry
this fan right now.

30:50.557 --> 30:52.684
I've got my socket drawn out.

30:52.684 --> 30:54.311
I've cut off the top.

30:54.311 --> 30:56.688
I'm gonna clean off
the scale a little bit.

30:56.688 --> 30:58.148
<i>It's the end of day one.</i>

30:58.148 --> 31:00.192
I've got the socket
onto the shaft.

31:00.192 --> 31:02.110
I'm not happy with where I'm at
on my blade.

31:02.110 --> 31:05.238
But it's so hot that I can't
continue working on it today.

31:07.240 --> 31:09.159
- There you go.
Good.

31:09.159 --> 31:11.036
<i>The tasks today are going</i>
<i>to be to get all</i>

31:11.036 --> 31:13.163
the pieces fit together
so that I can heat-treat

31:13.163 --> 31:14.664
<i>by the end of the night.</i>

31:14.664 --> 31:16.291
It's gonna be
a challenge to get

31:16.291 --> 31:18.335
the heat even on this piece,
being so long.

31:18.335 --> 31:21.213
I'm gonna concentrate most
of my effort on the blade,

31:21.213 --> 31:24.132
but I want to get the back end
up to heat first.

31:24.132 --> 31:25.842
There are several things
that could go wrong.

31:25.842 --> 31:28.136
<i>I could end up</i>
<i>with a soft weapon</i>

31:28.136 --> 31:31.890
or, worst-case scenario,
I could end up with a crack.

31:31.890 --> 31:33.600
It was hot.

31:33.600 --> 31:35.352
The question is,
was it good and hot?

31:35.352 --> 31:37.104
Little soft in here.

31:37.104 --> 31:39.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:39.314 --> 31:40.982
Those are hard.

31:40.982 --> 31:43.485
Hard. Hard.

31:43.485 --> 31:46.988
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:46.988 --> 31:49.366
I think we're good.

31:49.366 --> 31:51.326
- So my blade looks nice.

31:51.326 --> 31:53.829
It came out of the temper,
but I want to test it out.

31:53.829 --> 31:55.163
I want to make sure
it's gonna hold up.

31:55.163 --> 31:57.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:57.833 --> 31:59.334
Uh-oh.

31:59.334 --> 32:03.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:03.630 --> 32:06.091
[bleep].

32:06.091 --> 32:07.884
Oh, man.

32:07.884 --> 32:09.886
That sucks.
That sucks a lot.

32:09.886 --> 32:12.889
Even though my blade broke,
I've still got plenty of 1095.

32:12.889 --> 32:14.724
Okay, round two.

32:14.724 --> 32:17.227
<i>I can weld up another billet.</i>

32:17.227 --> 32:18.687
<i>I'm going at it with a press.</i>

32:18.687 --> 32:20.063
<i>I'm really drawing</i>
<i>this thing out.</i>

32:20.063 --> 32:22.190
<i>It's going good.</i>

32:22.190 --> 32:25.652
<i>I see, like, a little bit of</i>
<i>flame on the billet.</i>

32:25.652 --> 32:27.904
<i>So I'm wondering if maybe</i>
<i>a stray leaf or something</i>

32:27.904 --> 32:29.739
<i>got on it or maybe</i>
<i>a little bit of borax.</i>

32:29.739 --> 32:31.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.700 --> 32:32.993
[bleep].

32:32.993 --> 32:34.911
Dude!
Seriously?

32:34.911 --> 32:36.580
Like, come on.

32:36.580 --> 32:39.291
<i>Hydraulic line busted.</i>
<i>I lost my press.</i>

32:39.291 --> 32:41.501
<i>And that was the only way</i>
<i>to finish this thing.</i>

32:41.501 --> 32:43.336
I can't make a blade.

32:43.336 --> 32:44.588
Congratulations, Jason.

32:44.588 --> 32:44.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:46.965 --> 32:48.466
<i>Just kind of baffled.</i>

32:48.466 --> 32:51.261
<i>Two failures in one day.</i>

32:51.261 --> 32:53.180
I don't know.

32:53.180 --> 32:56.349
So Spicy Mike isn't
really a quitter.

32:56.349 --> 32:58.560
<i>I've still got a piece</i>
<i>of 5160.</i>

32:58.560 --> 33:00.812
I think I can pull something
off with that.

33:00.812 --> 33:04.733
<i>So my only goal for tomorrow</i>
<i>is nothing going wrong...</i>

33:04.733 --> 33:07.652
<i>or at least a lot less things.</i>

33:07.652 --> 33:09.446
I'm just glad
day three is over.

33:09.446 --> 33:10.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:10.989 --> 33:12.657
<i>- I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

33:12.657 --> 33:14.367
I don't have a whole lot
of work to do today.

33:14.367 --> 33:16.453
I just basically need to put
all the parts together

33:16.453 --> 33:18.413
and try to make 'em
look pretty.

33:18.413 --> 33:21.458
First thing anybody notices
on the beach is the butt,

33:21.458 --> 33:23.376
so I got to make sure
this thing looks good.

33:23.376 --> 33:30.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:30.383 --> 33:33.053
Ha ha! Nice.

33:33.053 --> 33:35.138
It will cut.
It will kill.

33:35.138 --> 33:36.556
[chicken clucks]

33:36.556 --> 33:38.725
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:38.725 --> 33:41.436
<i>- Considering how this process</i>
<i>started really bad</i>

33:41.436 --> 33:42.854
<i>and continued</i>
<i>to be really bad,</i>

33:42.854 --> 33:44.689
<i>I got a lot done.</i>

33:44.689 --> 33:46.024
<i>And I got caught up</i>
<i>to where I'm pretty sure</i>

33:46.024 --> 33:47.609
<i>that I can turn in something.</i>

33:47.609 --> 33:49.819
So today I really want to get
my butt cap made

33:49.819 --> 33:51.696
<i>and put on,</i>
<i>and I want to get</i>

33:51.696 --> 33:53.156
<i>all the finishing touches put</i>
<i>on the shaft.</i>

33:53.156 --> 33:54.824
Considering
my very first blade

33:54.824 --> 33:56.618
turned out
to be complete butts,

33:56.618 --> 33:59.037
<i>it would make total sense</i>
<i>to make a butt cap</i>

33:59.037 --> 34:00.580
out of the broken pieces
from it.

34:00.580 --> 34:05.460
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:05.460 --> 34:07.003
Here we go.

34:07.003 --> 34:08.630
It's gonna go everywhere.

34:08.630 --> 34:10.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:10.090 --> 34:11.925
Just want to see all
of the work

34:11.925 --> 34:13.927
<i>that I put into this thing</i>
<i>go to something.</i>

34:13.927 --> 34:20.225
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:20.225 --> 34:22.811
- Jason, Mike,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:22.811 --> 34:24.729
You guys have had five days
at your home forges

34:24.729 --> 34:26.690
to work on your finale weapons.

34:26.690 --> 34:28.024
Jason, how did it go?

34:28.024 --> 34:30.068
- It went pretty well.

34:30.068 --> 34:32.237
<i>Made a 33-layer Damascus</i>
<i>billet for the crescent blade.</i>

34:32.237 --> 34:34.322
<i>Used a hickory shaft.</i>

34:34.322 --> 34:36.408
We'll see if you guys
can break it.

34:36.408 --> 34:37.993
- All right, Spicy Mike.

34:37.993 --> 34:39.577
How hot did it get
at your forge?

34:39.577 --> 34:41.496
- It was pretty toasty.

34:41.496 --> 34:44.666
<i>I got a 5160 all one piece</i>
<i>shaft crescent.</i>

34:44.666 --> 34:47.711
<i>It's an ash shaft</i>
<i>with a cord wrap.</i>

34:47.711 --> 34:51.339
- All right, gentlemen,
this is the weapons tests.

34:51.339 --> 34:53.091
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

34:53.091 --> 34:54.968
and, up first, the kill test.

34:54.968 --> 34:56.136
Doug.

34:56.136 --> 34:57.971
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:57.971 --> 35:00.348
- To find out what kind
of lethal damage

35:00.348 --> 35:03.018
your weapon will do,
I will inflict lethal cuts

35:03.018 --> 35:05.979
and thrusts on both of these
ballistics dummies.

35:05.979 --> 35:07.647
Jason, you're up first.
You ready?

35:07.647 --> 35:09.524
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

35:09.524 --> 35:16.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:25.081 --> 35:26.583
- [exhales sharply]

35:26.583 --> 35:32.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.047 --> 35:34.049
- That was the coolest thing
I've ever seen.

35:34.049 --> 35:37.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:37.093 --> 35:38.678
- All right, Jason.

35:38.678 --> 35:41.348
This weapon is fast.
It's maneuverable.

35:41.348 --> 35:43.350
Your tip here is sharp enough
to penetrate

35:43.350 --> 35:45.393
and lacerate on the way out.

35:45.393 --> 35:48.772
The only one issue here
is that it did pick up a bend.

35:48.772 --> 35:51.983
But overall, your weapon, sir,
will kill.

35:51.983 --> 35:53.443
- Thank you.

35:53.443 --> 35:54.986
- All right, Spicy Mike,
you ready?

35:54.986 --> 35:55.987
- [chuckles]
Let's do it.

35:55.987 --> 35:58.031
- Let's do this.

35:58.031 --> 36:01.409
- I already watched Jason's
blade take a pretty good set.

36:01.409 --> 36:03.870
<i>If his took a set,</i>
<i>and I know he's a good maker,</i>

36:03.870 --> 36:06.456
mine's probably gonna take
some damage, too.

36:06.456 --> 36:13.338
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:17.676 --> 36:19.386
- [exhales sharply]

36:19.386 --> 36:25.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:31.106 --> 36:33.149
- [laughs]
- That's awesome.

36:33.149 --> 36:34.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:34.693 --> 36:37.112
- Did I do that?
- [laughs]

36:37.112 --> 36:39.531
- Spicy Mike,
your qinglong ji,

36:39.531 --> 36:41.991
it's wide enough to break bone
as I was thrusting

36:41.991 --> 36:43.743
into the chest cavity.

36:43.743 --> 36:47.205
It's a light, fast weapon,
and, most importantly,

36:47.205 --> 36:48.456
it will kill.

36:48.456 --> 36:50.291
- Thank you.

36:50.291 --> 36:52.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:52.836 --> 36:54.254
- All right, gentlemen,

36:54.254 --> 36:55.880
now it's my turn,
the strength test.

36:55.880 --> 36:58.258
To test the strength
and overall construction

36:58.258 --> 37:00.260
of your qinglong jis,
I will be using

37:00.260 --> 37:02.095
the crescent part
of the blade to try

37:02.095 --> 37:04.055
to break off these spears.

37:04.055 --> 37:05.557
Then it's on
to the drum stab

37:05.557 --> 37:06.933
using the front edge
of that blade.

37:06.933 --> 37:09.853
Now, remember, this test
is not about what

37:09.853 --> 37:11.604
your blade do to the target,

37:11.604 --> 37:13.982
but what these targets
can do to your blades.

37:13.982 --> 37:15.400
All right, Jason, you're up.
Are you ready?

37:15.400 --> 37:17.736
- Yes, sir.
- Okay.

37:17.736 --> 37:20.321
- Both of our blades performed
very well in the kill test,

37:20.321 --> 37:22.615
<i>but mine picked up</i>
<i>that little kink.</i>

37:22.615 --> 37:25.118
I'm gonna need to do very well
in the further tests

37:25.118 --> 37:27.078
if I hope to win
this competition.

37:27.078 --> 37:29.122
<i>I'm a little nervous</i>
<i>about how this is gonna go.</i>

37:29.122 --> 37:30.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:48.558 --> 37:50.477
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:50.477 --> 37:51.686
- All right, Jason,
well, this has got

37:51.686 --> 37:53.772
some serious heft to it.

37:53.772 --> 37:56.024
That bend didn't change any.

37:56.024 --> 37:57.859
What I do like to see
is the fact

37:57.859 --> 37:59.652
that your edges are just fine.

37:59.652 --> 38:01.404
It's a strong weapon,

38:01.404 --> 38:03.281
definitely did what it's
supposed to do.

38:03.281 --> 38:04.908
It's a good job.
- Thank you.

38:04.908 --> 38:06.409
- All right, Michael,
are you ready?

38:06.409 --> 38:08.203
- Yeah.

38:08.203 --> 38:15.084
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:30.600 --> 38:32.393
- Awesome.

38:32.393 --> 38:34.145
- All right, well,

38:34.145 --> 38:36.648
your weapon is still
in one piece.

38:36.648 --> 38:39.400
It's still sharp. Didn't lose
any of that blade at all.

38:39.400 --> 38:41.611
It's well done, good weapon.
- Thank you.

38:41.611 --> 38:44.072
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:44.072 --> 38:45.990
- Bladesmiths,
this is the sharpness test--

38:45.990 --> 38:47.784
the banner raise.

38:47.784 --> 38:49.619
Using the crescent's edge,
I will cut the rope,

38:49.619 --> 38:51.496
thereby raising the banner.

38:51.496 --> 38:54.666
Then I will test your flamberge
by slicing on the banner.

38:54.666 --> 38:56.000
Jason, you're up first.
You ready?

38:56.000 --> 38:57.710
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

38:57.710 --> 39:04.634
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:27.073 --> 39:28.616
- That was neat.

39:28.616 --> 39:30.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:30.076 --> 39:31.578
- All right, Jason,

39:31.578 --> 39:33.538
your crescent blade
is very sharp.

39:33.538 --> 39:35.874
It cut cleanly through
the rope, one and done.

39:35.874 --> 39:37.917
The edges of your flamberge
are sharp.

39:37.917 --> 39:41.504
The tip easily pierced it
and sliced all the way down.

39:41.504 --> 39:43.965
Overall, sir,
your weapon will cut.

39:43.965 --> 39:45.758
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:45.758 --> 39:47.510
All right, Michael, your turn.
You ready?

39:47.510 --> 39:49.679
- Let's do it.
- Let's do this.

39:49.679 --> 39:56.644
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:13.745 --> 40:15.872
All right, Mike,
on your crescent blade,

40:15.872 --> 40:17.540
the edge is sharp.

40:17.540 --> 40:19.667
Your flamberge over here,
the point is sharp.

40:19.667 --> 40:21.044
The edges are sharp.

40:21.044 --> 40:23.087
It was very easy to slide down.

40:23.087 --> 40:26.007
Overall, sir,
your weapon will cut.

40:26.007 --> 40:28.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.301 --> 40:31.512
- I really did test myself
in this process,

40:31.512 --> 40:33.973
<i>but I don't know</i>
<i>if I pulled it off or not.</i>

40:33.973 --> 40:36.309
- Jason, Michael,
you guys brought us

40:36.309 --> 40:38.519
exactly what we asked for--

40:38.519 --> 40:40.480
some high-performance
finale weapons.

40:40.480 --> 40:42.732
They're both fantastic,

40:42.732 --> 40:44.776
but, unfortunately,
there can only be one

40:44.776 --> 40:46.527
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:46.527 --> 40:50.865
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:50.865 --> 40:52.825
- Mike...

40:52.825 --> 40:55.411
you are the new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:55.411 --> 40:59.582
Jason, unfortunately your
weapon did not make the cut.

40:59.582 --> 41:01.793
- You guys both brought us
great weapons.

41:01.793 --> 41:04.295
But, Jason,
during the kill test,

41:04.295 --> 41:06.756
your weapon developed a bend,
and that's a structural issue.

41:06.756 --> 41:07.966
That's why
we're gonna send you home.

41:07.966 --> 41:09.425
- Yes, sir.

41:09.425 --> 41:13.221
- Jason, please surrender
your blade.

41:13.221 --> 41:15.056
<i>- I have no problems</i>
<i>with the judges' decision.</i>

41:15.056 --> 41:17.725
<i>That bend was</i>
<i>a critical failure.</i>

41:17.725 --> 41:19.852
I didn't come in here
to finish second.

41:19.852 --> 41:21.521
<i>I mean, honestly,</i>
<i>I'm disappointed.</i>

41:21.521 --> 41:24.107
<i>But I gained a lot</i>
<i>through this process.</i>

41:24.107 --> 41:25.984
I'm gonna take
a little bit of a break,

41:25.984 --> 41:28.319
<i>kind of regroup and then</i>
<i>decide what to do next.</i>

41:28.319 --> 41:31.447
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:31.447 --> 41:33.408
- Spicy Mike,
congratulations.

41:33.408 --> 41:35.451
You are our new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:35.451 --> 41:38.454
and that is a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

41:38.454 --> 41:40.623
Good job, man.
- [sighs]

41:40.623 --> 41:42.875
This is, like, the proudest
moment of my entire life.

41:42.875 --> 41:44.419
- Well, congratulations, man.

41:44.419 --> 41:46.254
You did some fantastic work.

41:46.254 --> 41:48.715
Please present your blade
to our judges.

41:48.715 --> 41:50.633
<i>- I'm--I-I won.</i>

41:50.633 --> 41:52.385
I'm just this crazy guy
with a weird nickname

41:52.385 --> 41:55.263
from the middle of nowhere,
but I did it!

41:55.263 --> 41:57.432
Uh, what do I do?
Where do I go?

41:57.432 --> 41:59.934
- Go get your money.
- Okay.

41:59.934 --> 42:01.477
- I'm gonna get
some stuff paid off,

42:01.477 --> 42:04.230
but after that,
I got to think about it.

42:04.230 --> 42:06.149
[groans, exhales sharply]

42:06.149 --> 42:07.275
Whoo!

42:07.275 --> 42:14.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>
